body:
As per google_authenticator.c,

```
  // Output QRCode using ANSI colors. Instead of black on white, we
  // output black on grey, as that works independently of whether the
  // user runs their terminal in a black on white or white on black color
  // scheme.
```

However, this fails on monochrome displays, as it shows as black on black.  I'm not sure such displays can be reliably detected (checking $TERM for xtermm and such might not catch them all), but a command line option could solve the problem.  qrencode deals with the issue mentioned above (the default colors of the user's terminal being unknown) by displaying white on black by default and having an option to reverse that (technically, both are options as it generates png by default).

qrencode also allows for ascii character format, which is hilarious.
